The Drops "Rain Rhythm Generator," made using a prefab PAM8403 audio amplifier board wired up in a feedback loop with a candle "flicker" LED. The LED generates random square wave pulses that are audible when routed through a capacitor. When feedbacked, these pulses turn into clicks that sound like rain on a metal roof, particularly when the audio is played through a piezo disc. There are a few switches that alter the feedback path, adjusting the instrument's rhythms. The 8403 chip and the LED can be voltage starved to alter the rhythm and timbre of the sound. There is also an LFO-driven relay in the installation version of this instrument that shorts the output audio, rhythmically muting the circuit. The body of the installation instrument is made from children's air dry foam clay, coated in epoxy. Drops is a companion to the Soprano Screecher, providing sounds that are delayed and modulated by that instrument.
